          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build and cook",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a pan over medium heat. Fry the {{onion}} for 4 minutes. Add the {{garlic}}, {{chilli-powder}}, {{cumin-ground}}, {{smoked-paprika}}, and {{tomato-puree}} and stir for 1 minute. Transfer to the slow cooker. Add the {{red-lentils}}, {{kidney-beans}}, {{tinned-tomatoes}}, {{stock-vegetable}}, {{sea-salt-fine}}, and {{black-pepper}}. Cook on low for 6 hours, until the lentils have dissolved into the sauce and the chilli is thick. Taste and adjust seasoning, start with half the chilli powder and taste at the end before adding more.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Start with 0.5 teaspoon and taste at the end. Stir in a spoonful of soured cream or yoghurt to cool the heat in individual bowls",
              "cause": "UK chilli powder is pure ground chilli, much hotter than US chili powder blend",
              "symptom": "Chilli too spicy for the household"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add 100 to 200 ml boiling water and stir. The correct consistency should be thick but spoonable",
              "cause": "Lentils absorbed all the liquid",
              "symptom": "Chilli very thick, almost solid"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Kidney beans in a 6-hour slow cooker hold their shape well. If they are dissolving, reduce the cook time to 5 hours next time",
              "cause": "Very long cook time",
              "symptom": "Kidney beans disintegrating"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lentil chilli is one of the best batch-cook options in this collection: cheap, nutritious, and improved by freezing and reheating. It serves six comfortably and the ingredients cost very little. Serve over rice, with jacket potatoes, or with soured cream, grated cheddar, and tortilla chips on a relaxed evening.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
